We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:

inform the Provincial Treasurer that the provision for granting discount on RPT as provided under the New Revenue Code of Palawan is in conflict with Section 246 of RA No. 7160, Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 and Section 177 of the LTOM;

propose to the Provincial Treasurer the issuance of a revised Notice of Payment for CY 2018 or any other means to disseminate information to taxpayers, clarifying that RPT payments made during the first quarter of the year are not considered “advanced” but instead “prompt” and subject only to 10% discount;

collect the amount of under-collection of RPT due from taxpayers for CY 2018 but only after providing them clear and sufficient information on the correct discounts and taxes due, notwithstanding the issuance of a Notice of Delinquency in accordance with Section 254 of RA No. 7160 and Article 345 of its IRR; and

henceforth, adhere to Article 342 of the IRR of RA No. 7160 in granting discounts on RPT payments.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor, being also the Chairman of MPOC and MADAC, coordinate with the MBO and the Cuyo Municipal Police Station in order to:

submit a justification on the validity of cash advances drawn from CF despite lack of specific appropriation for POP in the Annual Budget;

obtain a Certification from the Police Station highlighting in concrete details the circumstances which require the urgency in allocating CF;

reconcile the approved POP with the Itemized Statement thereof and exclude any unrelated program or activity;

provide the POP with complete references to the AIP regarding the proposed programs and activities, along with excerpts supporting the same;

obtain a Resolution of the MPOC declaring approval by two-thirds of its members on the release and use of CF; and

henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of COA-DBM-DILG-GCG-DND Joint Circular No. 2015-01 dated January 8, 2015.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should submit the AAPSI to the COA Audit Team timely, completely and accurately. The said AAPSI must indicate thereto the following:
Reference Number;
Audit Observations;
Audit Recommendations;
Agency Action Plan (Action Plan, Person Responsible and Target Implementation Date);
Status of Implementation;
Reason for Partial/ Delay/ Non-Implementation, if applicable; and
Action Taken/ Action to be taken.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor should submit the AAPSI to the
COA Audit Team timely, completely and accurately. The said AAPSI must indicate
thereto the following:
 a. Reference Number;
 b. Audit Observations;
 c. Audit Recommendations;
 d. Agency Action Plan (Action Plan, Person Responsible and Target
Implementation Date);
 e. Status of Implementation;
 f. Reason for Partial/ Delay/ Non-Implementation, if applicable; and
 g. Action Taken/ Action to be taken.

We recommended for the Municipal Mayor the following:
• Instruct the ICO-Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to regularly reconcile their respective books to accounts for any difference in the cash account balances;
• Require the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to immediately transmit to the Municipal Accountant the documents pertaining to all unrecorded transactions reflected in the BRS to facilitate recording thereof in the books of accounts provided they are valid and proper disbursements/transactions. Henceforth, the ICO-Municipal Treasurer strictly ensure that all documents pertaining to checks released and all other bank transactions shall be submitted promptly and intact to the Municipal Accountant for proper recording in the books;
• The ICO-Municipal Treasurer to deposit immediately all the cash collections in her custody with the authorized government depository bank, in compliance with Section 32 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I. Likewise, she should submit an explanation letter for not depositing her collections intact and promptly;
• The ICO-Municipal Treasurer to comply with Section 59 of NGAS Manual on the procedures for the stale checks. Accordingly, the Municipal Accountant should make the necessary adjustments in the books to account for the stale checks, provided they are supported with the original disbursement vouchers and other supporting documents.

We recommended that: 
• The management should send Demand Letters to those Accountable Officers to immediately settle their cash advances with due recourse to the consequences that may be instituted as enumerated above;
• In the case of the deceased, the management should request from COA to write-off the accounts. However, this presupposes that the management should go first with the remaining estate of the deceased without prejudice to the principle of relativity of the obligation;
• The management should see to it that officers and employees who will retire, resign or transfer to other agency are required to settle first their accountabilities before the issuance of clearance certificates to them; and
• The management should make other appropriate action such as, but not limited to, institutions of sanctions as provided for under Section 5.1.3 and 5.9 of COA Circular No. 97-002.
